description.value: A fragmentary plaster front-mould for a terracotta figure of Harpokrates, draped with a himation, and seated on the ground, the legs extending to his right (in the impression). His finger is to his mouth, and his head is shaven, with a side-lock, and he wears a Double Crown and a ribbon tied round his forehead, with a lotus bud on each side of the crown. He holds his pot with his left hand and the glans of his large phallus rests on his plinth, which is plain and almost flat-fronted. On the edge are six registration hollows for aligning the lost rear-mould; four are conical and two rectangular. The mould is made of fine white plaster, backed up with a thick layer of drab coarse plaster.

description.value: A white plaster rear-mould for a terracotta standing figure of Sarapis. He probably does not wear a chiton, but certainly has a himation over the impression’s left shoulder. At the front, the missing mould would probably have shown the himation falling down from the left shoulder, while the other end of this mantle covered him from the waist down, its rolled upper edge is caught up by his left lower arm and hanging by his side. The right arm was probably made separately and applied. He wears a modius, apparently with floral decoration; the hair is long. The rear of the right foot appears in this mould, and seems to be sandalled or booted. On the edges are six registration bosses to align the two moulds. There is slight damage to the bottom and to the rounded back of the mould.

description.value: Waist to mid-legs of a hand-modelled female clay figurine, broken at both ends. The figure may have been seated, but if so it was leaning back at a marked angle. A relatively large pubic triangle is marked by three thickly incised lines, while on the reverse the buttocks are large and carefully shaped. The hips taper in towards the waist, which would have been quite narrow. The figure has been modelled in two strips and joined vertically, the join smoothed along the front face but not along the reverse so that it delineates the buttocks and legs here, but also continues along the lower back. The dark brown mud is very fine and shows inclusions of mica.

description.value: Lower part of a clay figurine, plaque type. On the lower front face is a fairly carefully marked pubic triangle formed of four rows of dots. Above this are two groups of three dots that lie close to the broken upper edge, but may be complete. They probably mark tattoos or scarification. The dots are consistent in shape and size, and have perhaps been made with a circular metal point. The figure is quite well modelled, with flat faces. The base is not perfectly flat, but as the figure is quite thick it may have stood upright. The dark brown mud is very fine and shows inclusions of mica. On the back face and in the break several cracks.

description.value: Modelled female clay figurine with prominent buttocks and pubic triangle, and finished lower legs which are rounded off without any shaping of the knees or feet. The buttocks project markedly out from behind, but there is relatively little attempt to shape the hips, waist or thighs. A pubic triangle is marked fairly roughly, and placed quite low down, as a group of lightly incised lines in which are four dots. A separate circular dot above marks a navel. The figure is a relatively narrow and delicate example, although not very finely made. It has been formed as two separate hand-modelled strips, joined together vertically. The join is not particularly neat and has not been smoothed, apart from where the pubic triangle has been marked. One strip is pushed into the other somewhat, and was probably thicker to begin with.

description.value: Part of a figurine or a vessel in the shape of an animal head, probably a bovide. The clay is fired and shows some voids from chaff, the object had originally a red slip that is mostly eroded now. The ears are partly chipped off, preserved until the neck where the head was attached to the vessel or main body of the object. The part under the chin is reinforced by additional clay. The mouth is pierced and also in the end of the neck a small perforation is visible, not clear if these two holes are joint especially as the holes are very thin. If so the water would have run out of the mouth of the bovide.

description.value: Very roughly formed clay object, in the shape of a slightly bent cone with a flat base that is a bit wider than the upper part of the object. Unsmoothed and slightly irregular surface. At the underside in the base the impression of a scarab-like seal-impression of a almost round shape with a flat wide band running around the motif. The motif consists of a papyrus plant (M26) in the lower part and another sign that looks like a flying vulture in protection gesture above with both wings downwards. The seal-impression has a diameter of 1.5-1.7 cm. A thick salt crystal accretion on the surface by the base. The clay was hardened after excavation.

description.value: Small and quite delicately modelled clay figurine preserved from the base of the neck to the upper legs, with large buttocks and thighs, a narrow waist and very small breasts. The figure may have sat, leaning back at an angle. It has been modelled in two strips joined vertically, the join largely smoothed along the torso, although just visible along the back. The join delineates the thighs, at the top of which on the front is a slightly circular interruption that is just possibly a pubic feature. On the upper torso are two small circular breasts that are probably applied separately. Relatively little space has been given to the torso, but it has been neatly done. Two arm stumps project horizontally, but too little is preserved to determine their posture. description.value: Big fragment of a clay sealing with a convex outer surface, probably following a larger vessel or similar object, used as jar stopper, with an approximate diameter of 30 to 35 cm. The object has two rear sides so that it has a triangular section. One rear shows two parallel lines slightly raised above the surface that might be impressions caused by the ribbing of a vessel. Also a larger inclusion of a white lime fragment is visible on this side. The second underside shows a slightly uneven surface and an area of rectangular voids that might originate from organic material as larger charcoal particles are still visible in the clay here. The outer surface shows seven impressions of a small circular seal with a motif that was cut only very shallow and is therefore not visible anymore.

description.value: Almost intact clay figure, including a highly stylised head. The figure has the form of a flat rectangular plaque, which flares out very gently towards the base in profile. It has been modelled with reasonable care. Two widely spaced holes, surrounded by circular interruptions in the surface of the clay, mark areas where breasts have broken away. No navel, pubic triangle or body decoration has been marked. The head has been applied separately and slightly off centre, as a low flat disc. There is little room to show facial features, and none have been marked. The clay along the base of the figure has been pinched out, especially along the reverse, but the figure seems unlikely to have stood unsupported. Just along the top of the ridge on the front face, which is not particularly distinct, is a faint horizontal incision that is perhaps deliberate. The dark brown mud is very fine and shows inclusions of mica.

description.value: Figurine of unfired clay depicting a stylized naked woman. Relatively thick plaque figure with a roughly rectangular patch of quite deep dots on its lower front face. One is fairly central and slightly rounder than the others and is perhaps a navel. Above, there is a slightly disruption in the surface of the clay, probably where applied breasts have become detached. The plaque tapers towards its top and is here broken away but with the remains of a small hole, about 1mm in diameter, suggesting that a head was once attached by means of a peg. description.value: Fragment of a clay figurine, showing the waist to thighs of a female with very pronounced buttocks. The figure was probably in a seated posture, but leaning back quite markedly. The hips are somewhat pronounced in profile but the focus is on the buttocks projecting from the reverse face. There is no clear effort to model the waist although it is somewhat thinner than the thighs. The figure is reasonably well modelled but not entirely symmetrical. It has been formed by modelling two separate lengths of clay and joining them vertically. Unusually, no attempt has been made to smooth the clay across the join. There is a very thin ridge of clay between the two joined halves, especially visible on the back, which is perhaps the remains of mud slurry used as an adhesive. The dark brown mud is very fine and shows inclusions of mica.

description.value: Large, solid clay figurine, almost intact. It is rectangular, flaring out very gently in profile towards the base. The faces are not perfectly flat, but it has been fairly carefully modelled. The base is gently curved and the figure would not have stood upright on its own. The top tapers to a slight projection, the neck, in which is a small hole that might have facilitated the attachment of a head by means of a peg, although it is not a very substantial depression. description.value: Upper part of a a limestone figurine of a naked male youth (kouros); both legs are missing below the hips but the archaic Greek style of the body suggests that one leg was pushed slighly forward; the figure is shown frontally with an hourglass-shaped body, narrow hips and small pectorals (nipples indicated), but a somewhat plump stomach; his clenched left hand is held to his chest; the right arm is broken off at the shoulder.    The face is triangular with rounded edges; almond-shaped eyes (in deep, ridged sockets): traces of a black painted eyeball on the right eye; large ear-lobes; full lips with a slight smile. Wig-like hair, except for the three tresses falling on each side of the shoulders of hair, ending in sharp points and incised horizontally in the lower parts; a line of curls along the forehead; at the back are five tresses (and possibly the remains of a sixth) ended in triangles, but lacking the incisions of the front.
